"The soil throughout most parts of our district consists of a heavy clay, unsuitable for such market-gardening as is largely carried on in the rich black mould of South-West Middlesex. Nor was this clayey soil, even under the most favourable economic conditions, well adapted for cultivation by the plough. At all events, under the stress of foreign competition in our grain-markets, the local farmers have almost entirely abandoned the growing of cereals; while"